-- State landlord/tenant law seed — batch (generated by genStateLawSeed.ts).
-- Sourced from official .gov statutes 2026-06-11; every value cited + independently verified
-- against the quoted statute text before seeding. Provisions attach to each state's 'residential'
-- act; a topic absent for a state = no statutory value exists (NOT invented). Hedged + dated +
-- disclaimered at surface time per the S442 posture. States: CA, TX, FL, NY, PA, IL, OH, GA.
--
-- SOURCING NOTES (nuances the figures alone don't capture — read before relying on a value):
-- [CA] Sourced from official leginfo.legislature.ca.gov statute text.
-- [CA] DELIBERATELY OMITTED (no statutory value exists — would be invented otherwise):
-- [CA] - late_fee_max_pct: California has NO statutory percentage cap on residential late fees. Late fees are governed by the liquidated-damages reasonableness standard of Civ. Code § 1671(d) (a residential late fee is void unless it is a reasonable estimate of actual damages). Courts treat ~5% as a practical safe harbor, but that is case law, not a number in the statute — so no value is recorded.
-- [CA] - late_fee_grace_days: No statutory grace period before a residential late fee may apply.
-- [CA] DEPOSIT CAP NUANCE (AB 12, eff. July 1, 2024): Standard max is 1 month's rent regardless of furnished/unfurnished (the old 2-month/3-month furnished distinction was repealed). Small-landlord exception under § 1950.5(c)(2): max is 2 months' rent if the landlord is a natural person (or an LLC wholly owned by natural persons) AND owns no more than two residential rental properties collectively totaling no more than four dwelling units. Recorded value reflects the general 1-month cap.
-- [CA] DEPOSIT RETURN: § 1950.5(g)(1) sets the 21-calendar-day itemized-statement/return deadline. (Some sources cite subsection (h); the controlling 21-day text is in (g)(1) in the current codification — section reorganized over amendments. Verify exact subsection letter at annual refresh.)
-- [CA] NOTICE TO VACATE: 60 days is the default for landlord-initiated termination of a residential month-to-month tenancy; drops to 30 days under § 1946.1(c) if any tenant has resided less than one year. Tenant-initiated notice need only equal the length of the periodic term (typically 30 days). Recorded the 60-day landlord default as the conservative min.
-- [CA] ACT COVERAGE:
-- [CA] - Residential Civil Code hiring chapter (§§ 1925–1954) + § 1950.5 covers apartments and single_family. Storage rented as part of a residential tenancy falls under the same lease; standalone self-storage is governed separately by the California Self-Service Storage Facility Act (Bus. & Prof. Code § 21700 et seq.) — not researched here, flag if storage is a primary unit type.
-- [CA] - Mobilehome Residency Law (Ch. 2.5, §§ 798+) governs mobilehome/manufactured-home parks. An RV that occupies a mobilehome site for 9+ continuous months is pulled under the MRL rather than the RV law.
-- [CA] - Recreational Vehicle Park Occupancy Law (Ch. 2.6, §§ 799.20–799.79) governs RV park lots; an RV occupant becomes a "tenant" after 30+ consecutive days and a "resident" after 9 months. The residential §1950.5 deposit cap / §1954 entry rules do NOT apply to MRL/RVPOL tenancies — those acts have their own provisions.
-- [CA] - Commercial: California has no dedicated commercial landlord-tenant protection act; commercial leases run on contract/common law under the general hiring provisions (§§ 1925 et seq.). SB 1103 (2024) added limited protections (translation, cost recovery, termination notice via amended § 1946.1) for "qualified commercial tenants" (microenterprises, small restaurants ≤10 employees, nonprofits ≤20 employees) only — not commercial tenants generally.
-- [CA] The residential provisions reflect statute current as of the AB 12 (2024) deposit reform. Annual-refresh candidate: confirm § 1950.5 subsection lettering and any further deposit/entry amendments each Nov/Dec cycle.
--
-- [TX] Entry notice: OMITTED — Texas has NO statute requiring advance notice for landlord entry to a residential dwelling; entry rights are governed by the lease/common law (no hours value to cite). Deposit cap: OMITTED — Texas does NOT cap the security deposit amount as months of rent; no statutory ceiling exists in ch. 92 subch. C. Late fee: § 92.019 is a safe-harbor, not a hard cap — fees above 12%/10% are still permissible if they do not exceed the landlord's uncertain damages from late payment; the 12% figure applies to structures with ≤4 dwelling units and 10% to structures with >4 units (encoded the 12% as the headline max). Late-fee grace: 2 full days delinquent before a late fee may be assessed. Notice-to-vacate: § 91.001 lives in ch. 91 (general provisions, also covers commercial), but it is the controlling month-to-month termination rule for residential; statute frames it as 'one month' (≈30 days) and parties may agree to a different period in a signed instrument. RV (rv_spot): NO separate RV-tenancy act in Texas; ch. 94 covers only manufactured/mobile-home communities (situating a manufactured home), not RVs — long-term RV-pad tenancies fall under general residential/common law or innkeeper law depending on duration, so rv_spot is left unmapped. Storage: no dedicated act; self-service storage liens are in Tex. Prop. Code ch. 59 (not a landlord-tenant act) — mapped storage to commercial (ch. 93) as the closest landlord-tenant fit. Commercial: ch. 93 covers only limited matters (utility interruption, lockout, property removal); most commercial leasing is common-law/contract-governed.
--
-- [FL] DEPOSIT CAP: Florida § 83.49 sets NO maximum on the security deposit amount (no months-of-rent cap) — deposit_max_months OMITTED, not invented. LATE FEES: Ch. 83 pt. II contains NO statutory late-fee cap and NO statutory grace period — both are purely lease-defined; late_fee_max_pct and late_fee_grace_days OMITTED. DEPOSIT RETURN nuance: § 83.49(3)(a) is a dual deadline — 15 days to return if NO claim is imposed; 30 days to send written notice of intent to impose a claim. Modeled deposit_return_days as the 30-day outer bound (claim path); evidence quotes both clauses. Note § 83.49 also requires interest on certain held deposits ("together with interest if otherwise required") — relevant to GAM's S188/S190 deposit-interest tables.\n\nACT COVERAGE: Ch. 83 pt. II (Residential) governs apartments + single_family. RV long-term mapped here: standalone RV occupancy is regulated under ch. 513 (Mobile Home & Recreational Vehicle Parks), but ch. 513 creates a rebuttable presumption that an RV occupant who stays >6 months with park-operator knowledge is NONtransient, invoking the eviction procedures of ch. 83 pt. II — so rv_spot is tagged to the Residential act as the closest governing tenancy law. Mobile homes on rented park lots (parks of 10+ lots) are governed by ch. 723 (Florida Mobile Home Act); parks with fewer than 10 lots fall back to ch. 83 pt. II. Commercial = ch. 83 pt. I (Nonresidential Tenancies). Storage = ch. 83 pt. III (Self-Service Storage Space). Official source throughout: Florida Legislature / Online Sunshine (leg.state.fl.us). All entry/deposit/termination quotes verified against the official statute text.
--
-- [NY] RESIDENTIAL provisions are split across two statutes: deposit caps/return live in General Obligations Law § 7-108 (2019 HSTPA reform); late fees and termination notice live in Real Property Law art. 7. ENTRY NOTICE OMITTED: New York has NO statewide statute fixing an advance-entry-notice hour count — AG guidance only says \"reasonable prior notice,\" so no value is encoded. NOTICE-TO-VACATE is TIERED by tenancy length under RPL § 226-c(2): 30 days (<1 yr), 60 days (1–2 yrs), 90 days (>2 yrs); the encoded min reflects the shortest (30 days) for a basic month-to-month. RPL § 232-a (NYC) and § 232-b (outside NYC) cross-reference § 226-c for residential tenancies. DEPOSIT CAP has carve-outs: seasonal-use dwellings and owner-occupied co-ops may exceed one month. LATE FEE is a hard dual cap: lesser of $50 OR 5% of monthly rent, only after a 5-day grace. MOBILE HOME: RPL § 233 governs manufactured home parks (3+ year-round homes); has its own deposit-interest, lease-renewal, and 90-day fee-increase rules distinct from the general residential act. RV/travel trailers are EXPLICITLY EXCLUDED from § 233 and have no dedicated NY act — rv_spot is therefore unmapped to any act. COMMERCIAL/STORAGE: no dedicated NY commercial landlord-tenant act; governed by general RPL provisions + RPAPL art. 7 for proceedings; the residential deposit/late-fee/notice caps above do NOT apply to commercial tenancies.
--
-- [PA] DEPOSIT CAP: 2 months' rent in the first year, dropping to 1 month for the second/subsequent years and renewals (§ 250.511a); residential-only and non-waivable. NOTICE TO VACATE: § 250.501 ties the period to lease length — 15 days for leases of one year or less, 30 days for leases over one year (used 15 as the floor/min). Note PA's default month-to-month termination notice is commonly cited as 15 days under this section, but the statute frames it by lease term, not explicitly by 'month-to-month'; treat 15 as the statutory minimum. NO STATUTORY ENTRY NOTICE: PA has no statute requiring advance notice before landlord entry — governed entirely by the lease (entry_notice_hours omitted). NO LATE-FEE CAP / NO GRACE PERIOD: PA statutes do not cap late fees or mandate a grace period; courts apply a common-law reasonableness/liquidated-damages standard (late_fee_max_pct and late_fee_grace_days omitted — not invented). DEPOSIT RETURN ENFORCEMENT: § 250.512 imposes double-damages liability on a landlord who fails to return the difference within 30 days, and forfeiture of withholding rights if no written damage list is provided within 30 days. COMMERCIAL: PA has no separate commercial landlord-tenant act; commercial tenancies are governed by the 1951 Act plus common law, so it is mapped onto the residential act (its escrow/deposit caps in § 250.511a apply only to residential per the statute's 'rental of residential property' limiter). MOBILE/MANUFACTURED HOMES: the Manufactured Home Community Rights Act (68 P.S. § 398.1 et seq.) covers only residents who OWN their manufactured/mobile home and rent the lot in a community of 3+ homes; renters of a home within such a community fall back to the 1951 Act. RV/RECREATIONAL VEHICLES: no separate PA act. The MHCRA 'manufactured home' definition (§ 2) incorporates the federal HUD definition (42 U.S.C. § 5402(6)) and the PA Vehicle Code mobile-home definition (75 Pa.C.S. § 102), both of which exclude self-propelled/towable RVs and travel trailers — so rv_spot long-term tenancies are not covered by the MHCRA and default to the general 1951 Act / common-law contract. STORAGE: not a landlord-tenant act in PA; self-storage is governed by the separate PA Self-Service Storage Facility Act (a lien statute), outside this tenancy grouping.
--
-- [IL] VERIFIED against ilga.gov (Illinois General Assembly, official). Illinois has NO single consolidated residential landlord-tenant act; residential rules are split across the Security Deposit Return Act (765 ILCS 710), Security Deposit Interest Act (765 ILCS 715), Landlord and Tenant Act (765 ILCS 705), and the eviction/notice provisions in the Code of Civil Procedure (735 ILCS 5/9-201 et seq.).
-- [IL] OMITTED (no statewide statute — do NOT invent):
-- [IL] - deposit_max_months: NO statewide cap for standard residential. The Security Deposit Return Act sets no maximum. (Only the Mobile Home Act caps deposits at 1 month — 765 ILCS 745/12(b): 'Permitting the park owner to charge an amount in excess of one month's rent as a security deposit'.)
-- [IL] - late_fee_max_pct / late_fee_grace_days: NO statewide residential cap or grace period. (Only the Mobile Home Act mandates a 5-day grace — 765 ILCS 745/12(a): 'charge a penalty fee for late payment of rent without allowing a tenant a minimum of 5 days beyond the date the rent is due'. Local ordinances like the Chicago RLTO impose their own late-fee/entry rules, but those are municipal, not state statute.)
-- [IL] - entry_notice_hours: NO statewide statute requires advance notice for landlord entry to a residential dwelling. Entry notice is governed by local ordinance (e.g., Chicago RLTO 48 hours), not Illinois state law. Confirmed by reviewing every section of the Landlord and Tenant Act (765 ILCS 705).
-- [IL] NOTICE NUANCE: month-to-month = 30 days (735 ILCS 5/9-207(b)); week-to-week = 7 days (9-207(a)); year-to-year = 60 days (735 ILCS 5/9-205: 'in all cases of tenancy from year to year, 60 days' notice, in writing, shall be sufficient to terminate the tenancy at the end of the year'). Reported notice_to_vacate_days=30 as the month-to-month value. Note 9-207.5 imposes 90 days in residential foreclosure scenarios.
-- [IL] DEPOSIT RETURN NUANCE: The 45-day figure applies when the lessor furnishes NO itemized statement. If the lessor withholds for damage, it must furnish an itemized statement of damage within 30 days of the lessee vacating (765 ILCS 710/1(a)). The current statute applies to 'residential real property' generally — the older '5 or more units' threshold has been removed from subsection (a) of the current text.
-- [IL] MOBILE HOME ACT (765 ILCS 745): governs mobile/manufactured homes in parks. 'Mobile Home Park' = a tract with sites for 5 or more mobile/manufactured homes (765 ILCS 745/3(c)). The act's definition EXPLICITLY EXCLUDES RVs: 765 ILCS 745/3(b) — 'The term excludes campers and recreational vehicles.' Mobile-home-specific caps: deposit max 1 month (745/12(b)), late-fee 5-day grace (745/12(a)), and a 3% annual rent-increase cap was recently added.
-- [IL] RV SPOTS: Illinois has NO dedicated RV/recreational-vehicle tenancy act, and RVs are expressly carved out of the Mobile Home Act. Long-term RV-pad tenancies fall under the general residential/common-law framework (Security Deposit Return Act + 735 ILCS 5 notice provisions) with no RV-specific statutory provisions — so rv_spot is not mapped to any act here. The general notice statutes (9-205/9-207) apply by tenancy term regardless of unit type.
-- [IL] COMMERCIAL/STORAGE: No dedicated commercial landlord-tenant act. The notice-to-terminate statutes (735 ILCS 5/9-205, 9-207) apply to all tenancies by term, and the Landlord and Tenant Act (765 ILCS 705) contains general provisions. Self-storage is separately regulated by the Self-Service Storage Facility Act (770 ILCS 95) for lien/sale, not as a landlord-tenant deposit/notice regime.
-- [IL] URL note: ILGA migrated off the legacy ilcs3.asp URLs (now 404). Stable section text lives at https://www.ilga.gov/documents/legislation/ilcs/documents/{DocName}.htm and act-listing pages at https://www.ilga.gov/Legislation/ILCS/Articles?ActID=NNNN&ChapterID=62.
--
-- [OH] Residential act is ORC ch. 5321. CRITICAL OMISSIONS (statute does not specify, so not invented): (1) NO security deposit cap — ch. 5321 places no ceiling on deposit amount; the "$50 or one month's rent, whichever is greater" figure in § 5321.16(A) is only the threshold above which the landlord must PAY 5% annual INTEREST on the deposit if the tenant stays 6+ months, NOT a cap on the deposit. So deposit_max_months is omitted. (2) NO late_fee_max_pct in the residential act. (3) NO late_fee_grace_days in the residential act. (A 3-day grace + flat/percent late-fee 'reasonableness' rule DOES exist for SELF-SERVICE STORAGE at § 5322.05 and similar concepts in manufactured-home-park law, but NOT for general residential tenancies — do not map those to the residential act.)
-- [OH] entry_notice_hours (24h) is a REBUTTABLE PRESUMPTION of reasonableness under § 5321.04(A)(8), not an absolute statutory minimum — the statute requires 'reasonable notice' and presumes 24h reasonable absent contrary evidence.
-- [OH] notice_to_vacate: § 5321.17(B) = 30 days for month-to-month; § 5321.17(A) = 7 days for week-to-week (not captured as the topic enum targets month-to-month).
-- [OH] ACT SCOPE / UNIT-TYPE MAPPING:
-- [OH] - COMMERCIAL: Ohio has NO landlord-tenant statute for commercial leases. Ch. 5321 applies only to 'residential premises'; § 5321.01 expressly excludes commercial-type uses (and its exclusion list also names hotels, motels, RV parks, recreation camps, and dwelling units subject to the manufactured-home-park chapter). Commercial leases are governed by common law and the lease contract — no act provided for 'commercial' unit type.
-- [OH] - MOBILE_HOME / MANUFACTURED HOME PARKS: governed by ch. 4781 (Ohio Manufactured Homes Commission), which RECODIFIED the historical ch. 3733 manufactured-home-park tenant law. Some § 5321.01 cross-reference text still reads 'Chapter 3733' as the legacy citation. Current live chapter is 4781.
-- [OH] - RV_SPOT: Ohio has no dedicated long-term RV-tenancy act. Two relevant chapters: (a) ch. 4781 references a 'recreational vehicle parked in the manufactured home park' in its abandonment/possession provisions, so an RV occupying a manufactured-home-park lot can fall under 4781; (b) ch. 3729 licenses/regulates recreational vehicle parks and recreation camps as a public-health/licensing regime, NOT a tenancy-rights act. Mapped rv_spot to both 4781 (park-lot tenancy) and 3729 (RV park licensing) for coverage; the actual tenant-rights protections live in 4781 where applicable.
-- [OH] - STORAGE: ch. 5322 (Self-Service Storage Facilities) — lien/late-fee regime; § 5322.04 prohibits residential use.
-- [OH] UNCERTAINTY: WebFetch on § 5321.16 once mislabeled the interest threshold as a 'deposit cap' — verified against statutory text that it is an interest trigger, not a cap; confirmed no deposit-amount ceiling exists.
--
-- [GA] VERIFIED against the official current codified OCGA text (Georgia General Assembly public-access Title 44, sourced from the state's Lexis open-data publication). The Georgia General Assembly publishes the OCGA via a Lexis-hosted public-access portal linked from legis.ga.gov (advance.lexis.com/container?config=00JAAzZDgzNzU2ZC05MDA0LTRmMDItYjkzMS0xOGY3MjE3OWNlODI); legis.ga.gov has no per-section static URLs, so the act/section sourceUrl points to the official OCGA landing.
-- [GA] SINGLE GENERAL ACT: Georgia has ONE landlord-tenant statute (Title 44, Chapter 7) that governs ALL tenancy types — it is NOT limited to residential. Articles: Art.1 In General (44-7-1..24), Art.2 Security Deposits (44-7-30..37, residential-only carve-out), Art.3 Dispossessory/eviction (44-7-49..59), Art.4 Distress Warrants (44-7-70..82), Art.5 Croppers (44-7-100..103), Art.6 Abandoned Mobile Home Act (44-7-110+). No separate commercial, mobile-home-park, RV, or storage act exists. Commercial and residential share the same chapter; the security-deposit escrow/return rules (44-7-31..35) are the only residential-specific provisions.
-- [GA] MOBILE HOME / RV: There is NO Georgia mobile-home-park lot tenancy act. Several third-party sites falsely cite a 'Georgia Mobile Home Park Lot Act, O.C.G.A. § 44-7-60' with a 60-day rent-increase rule and a 1/12 cap — I confirmed against the official code that NO section 44-7-60 exists and no such act is codified (a 1974 Ga. L. Rev. note at 9 Ga. L. Rev. 212 even argued for the 'necessity for specific state legislation to deal with the mobile home park landlord-tenant relationship,' which Georgia never enacted). Mobile-home lot rentals and RV-spot rentals fall under the general Chapter 7. The only mobile-home-specific statute is Art.6 'Abandoned Mobile Home Act' (44-7-110+), which is about removing abandoned/blighted homes — not a tenancy/lot-rental regime — plus 44-7-82 (distress warrant applies to a tenant's mobile home).
-- [GA] PROVISIONS NOT IN STATUTE (correctly OMITTED, do not invent):
-- [GA] - deposit_max_months: NO statutory cap on security deposit amount. Scanned the entire security-deposit article (44-7-30..37) and chapter — zero deposit-amount cap language.
-- [GA] - entry_notice_hours: NO statutory advance-entry-notice requirement. Entry is purely a lease matter; case annotations under 44-7-1 note a landlord must reserve the right to enter via lease clause, and the official GA Landlord-Tenant Handbook lists landlord-entry circumstances/notice as a lease term to negotiate, not a statutory mandate.
-- [GA] - late_fee_max_pct / late_fee_grace_days: NO statutory late-fee cap and NO mandated grace period. 44-7-34 only references 'fees for late payment' as a permissible deposit deduction; the only 'grace period' in the chapter is the dispossessory pay-to-cure window, unrelated to rent late fees. The handbook treats grace periods/late charges as negotiable lease terms.
-- [GA] CITATION NUANCE on deposit return: the official codified 44-7-34(a) currently reads '30 days' (2018 amendment, HB 834, eff. 2018). Many secondary sources — and even the Georgia Dept. of Law consumer handbook — still say 'one month' (the pre-2018 text); the codified statute ('30 days') controls and is what I used. Security-deposit escrow/list/return rules (44-7-31,32,33,35) do NOT apply to a natural-person landlord who, with spouse and minor children, owns 10 or fewer rental units and self-manages (no third-party fee-based management) — 44-7-36 exemption; but 44-7-34's return obligation itself still applies to all landlords.
